        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Video marketing</strong> is the strategic use of video content — short-form social clips, long-form tutorials, product demos, testimonials, live streams, and paid video ads — to attract, educate, and convert target audiences across digital platforms. Unlike a single tactic, it is a channel category encompassing every format where moving images carry the marketing message, from a 15-second TikTok to a 45-minute webinar recording.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing / Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Video Content Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Video is not a trend. It is the default way humans now consume information online. Every major platform — Google, Instagram, TikTok, LinkedIn, Twitter/X — has restructured its algorithm to favour video distribution. Teams that build video into their core strategy compound the advantage every quarter. Teams that treat it as an add-on keep paying to stay still.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is video marketing?</h2>
        <p>Video marketing encompasses every deliberate use of video to achieve a marketing or business objective. That definition is intentionally broad because video appears at every stage of the customer journey and across every channel type:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Organic social video</strong> (TikTok, Instagram Reels, YouTube Shorts, LinkedIn video) — discovery and awareness</li>
          <li><strong>Long-form YouTube</strong> — education, consideration, SEO traffic</li>
          <li><strong>Paid video advertising</strong> (Meta in-feed, YouTube pre-roll, CTV) — targeted demand generation</li>
          <li><strong>Website video</strong> (hero video, product demos, testimonials) — conversion rate optimisation</li>
          <li><strong>Email video</strong> (thumbnail links to video) — nurture and re-engagement</li>
          <li><strong>Live streaming</strong> (Instagram Live, YouTube Live, LinkedIn Live) — real-time community and trust</li>
          <li><strong>Webinars and virtual events</strong> — pipeline generation and education</li>
        </ul>

        <p>What unites all these is the core advantage of the medium: video communicates emotion, demonstrates complexity, and builds trust at a speed and depth that text and static images cannot match. A 90-second product demo replaces a 10-page spec sheet for the majority of buyers.</p>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why video marketing matters in 2026</h2>
        <p>Three structural forces make video marketing a non-negotiable channel for any brand with a digital audience:</p>

        <h3>1. Algorithm preference</h3>
        <p>Every major social platform has restructured its content ranking to favour video, particularly short-form vertical video. Instagram distributes Reels to 22% more non-followers than static posts on average. TikTok's entire discovery mechanism is built around video. LinkedIn video posts generate 3x more reach than text-only posts. The algorithm tax on non-video content is real and growing.</p>

        <h3>2. Attention economics</h3>
        <p>The average attention span for digital content is 8 seconds. Video — particularly short-form video with a strong hook — is the only format that consistently wins that battle. Users who would scroll past a text post stop for an autoplay video. The format matches how people actually consume information when they are not in active reading mode.</p>

        <h3>3. Trust at scale</h3>
        <p>Video builds the kind of trust that closes deals. Hearing a founder explain their product, watching a customer describe their result, or seeing a feature work in real time transfers credibility in a way that written words cannot fully replicate. For B2B companies selling complex or high-ticket products, video collapses the sales cycle by doing pre-qualification at scale.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of video marketing content</h2>
        <p>Different video types serve different objectives. A common mistake is treating all video as interchangeable — using a product demo where an educational piece would work better, or a thought-leadership piece where a testimonial would close the deal faster.</p>

