        <h2 id="strategy">How to build a video marketing strategy</h2>
        <p>A video marketing strategy is not a content calendar. It is a system that connects production, distribution, and measurement to a specific business outcome. Here is a framework that works for teams of any size:</p>

        <h3>Step 1: Define the objective and the metric</h3>
        <p>Every video programme should be anchored to one primary business metric. For most B2B companies: pipeline generated from video-assisted leads. For B2C and e-commerce: conversion rate lift from product video. For content-led businesses: organic video reach and subscriber/follower growth. Without a clear metric, video budgets get allocated to the most visually impressive formats rather than the highest-converting ones.</p>

        <h3>Step 2: Map content to the funnel stage</h3>
        <p>Use the table above to identify which video types address your most important conversion gaps. If discovery is the problem, invest in short-form social. If conversion is the problem, invest in testimonials and demos. If retention is the problem, invest in educational content and webinars. Most teams under-invest in bottom-funnel video because it is less glamorous than viral content, but it has the most direct revenue impact.</p>

        <h3>Step 3: Build a production system, not one-off projects</h3>
        <p>The biggest predictor of video marketing success is consistency. Teams that publish one highly produced video per month consistently underperform teams that publish three to five lower-production videos per week. Volume enables algorithmic distribution. Establish a production pipeline with defined roles, templates, and approval workflows — then optimise for speed over perfection.</p>

        <h3>Step 4: Distribute on the right platforms</h3>
        <p>Native uploads outperform shared links on every platform. Upload the video directly to each platform rather than sharing a YouTube link on Instagram. Cross-post selectively — a TikTok video repurposed for LinkedIn Reels needs at least caption and hook adaptation for the different audience context.</p>

        <h3>Step 5: Measure and iterate</h3>
        <p>The essential metrics are: video completion rate (content quality), reach/impressions (distribution effectiveness), and click-through rate or conversion rate (commercial effectiveness). Review these at video level weekly and at channel level monthly. The videos with highest completion and highest CTR reveal your content formula — replicate and scale those, and retire the formats that underperform across both dimensions.</p>

        <h2 id="platforms">Video marketing platform guide</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Organic reach platforms (2026)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>TikTok</strong> — highest non-follower reach ceiling; best for B2C, creators, and B2B thought leadership</li>
              <li><strong>YouTube Shorts</strong> — feeds into long-form YouTube SEO; best for educational brands</li>
              <li><strong>Instagram Reels</strong> — large audience, slower-paced algorithm; strong for visual brands</li>
              <li><strong>LinkedIn video</strong> — B2B reach, underutilised; significant first-mover advantage</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Paid distribution platforms</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>YouTube pre-roll</strong> — intent-based targeting; effective for consideration stage</li>
              <li><strong>Meta in-feed video</strong> — broad targeting, strong creative testing; best for B2C</li>
              <li><strong>CTV / OTT</strong> — high reach, growing audience; best for brand awareness at scale</li>
              <li><strong>LinkedIn video ads</strong> — expensive CPMs but unmatched B2B targeting precision</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 video marketing best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Hook in 1-3 seconds.</strong> The first three seconds determine whether a viewer stays or scrolls. Start with the most compelling moment, not the setup.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimise for sound-off.</strong> 85% of social video is watched without sound in public. Every video needs either open captions or compelling visuals that work silently.</li>
          <li><strong>Shoot vertical first.</strong> For social distribution, produce in 9:16 as the master and adapt to other ratios. Landscape-first production consistently underperforms on mobile feeds.</li>
          <li><strong>One video, one message.</strong> Videos that try to communicate three ideas at once fail to communicate any of them. Focus each video on a single specific claim, question, or story.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a CTA.</strong> Every video should have a next step — follow, subscribe, click the link, leave a comment. Without a CTA, engagement stays on the platform and does not move buyers forward.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose systematically.</strong> A 45-minute webinar contains at least 10 short-form clips. A long-form YouTube video can become 5 Reels, a blog post, and 3 email campaigns. Extract maximum value from every production investment.</li>
          <li><strong>Test thumbnails separately.</strong> On YouTube, the thumbnail drives the click. Run A/B tests on thumbnails before optimising the video itself — thumbnail improvements often deliver a 2-3x CTR lift with no production cost.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish consistently.</strong> Algorithms on all platforms reward posting frequency. A consistent cadence of 3-5 short-form videos per week outperforms sporadic high-quality posts on every distribution metric.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common video marketing mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Starting with production quality instead of strategy.</strong> Expensive cameras do not fix poor positioning. Define the audience, message, and CTA before buying any equipment.</li>
          <li><strong>Making all videos the same length.</strong> Short-form, mid-form, and long-form serve different purposes. A library that is only 30-second clips misses consideration and retention; one that is only 20-minute tutorials misses discovery.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring analytics.</strong> Most teams create more content when performance drops instead of diagnosing what is not working. Check retention curves and completion rates before commissioning new work.</li>
          <li><strong>Sharing links instead of native uploads.</strong> A YouTube link posted to Instagram gets a fraction of the organic reach of a native Reels upload. Always upload natively to each platform.</li>
          <li><strong>No distribution amplification.</strong> Posting and praying is not a strategy. Use paid amplification to seed videos that show strong organic signals. Even $50-$100 in boosting can turn a good video into a great-performing one.</li>
        </ul>

